<h2><a name="break" id="break">break</a></h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
The  break keyword is used to break out of a do, for, or while loop. It is also
used to finish each clause of a switch statement, keeping the program from
“falling through” to the next case in the code. An example:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">     <span class="kw1">while</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span> x <span class="sy0">&lt;</span> <span class="nu0">100</span> <span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="br0">&#123;</span>
       <span class="kw1">if</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span> x <span class="sy0">&lt;</span> <span class="nu19">0</span> <span class="br0">&#41;</span>
         <span class="kw2">break</span>;
       <a href="http://www.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/009695399/functions/cout.html"><span class="kw3">cout</span></a> <span class="sy0">&lt;&lt;</span> x <span class="sy0">&lt;&lt;</span> endl;
       x++;
     <span class="br0">&#125;</span></pre>
<p>

A given break statement will break out of only the closest loop, no further. If
you have a triply-nested for loop, for example, you might want to include extra
logic or a goto statement to break out of the loop.
</p>

<p>
